04616nam a22007215i 9780801463051DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013937803  a97808014630517 a10.7591/97808014630512doi  a(DE-B1597)478593  a(OCoLC)979630552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPA6648.P6 7aPOE0080002bisacsh04a871.012231 aPrudentius, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origin of Sin :bAn English Translation of the "Hamartigenia" /cPrudentius. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Classical Philology ;v6100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Translations and Editions -- tThe Origin of Sin: An English Translation -- tPreface -- tThe Origin of Sin -- tAn Interpretive Essay -- tIntroduction -- t1. Writing in Chains -- t2. Figuring It Out -- t3. Seeking Hidden Truth -- t4. Falling into Language -- t5. Under Assault -- t6. Generation of Vipers -- t7. Signs of Woe -- t8. In Aenigmate -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAurelius Prudentius Clemens (348–ca. 406) is one of the great Christian Latin writers of late antiquity. Born in northeastern Spain during an era of momentous change for both the Empire and the Christian religion, he was well educated, well connected, and a successful member of the late Roman elite, a man fully engaged with the politics and culture of his times. Prudentius wrote poetry that was deeply influenced by classical writers and in the process he revived the ethical, historical, and political functions of poetry. This aspect of his work was especially valued in the Middle Ages by Christian writers who found themselves similarly drawn to the Classical tradition.Prudentius's Hamartigenia, consisting of a 63-line preface followed by 966 lines of dactylic hexameter verse, considers the origin of sin in the universe and its consequences, culminating with a vision of judgment day: the damned are condemned to torture, worms, and flames, while the saved return to a heaven filled with delights, one of which is the pleasure of watching the torments of the damned. As Martha A. Malamud shows in the interpretive essay that accompanies her lapidary translation, the first new English translation in more than forty years, Hamartigenia is critical for understanding late antique ideas about sin, justice, gender, violence, and the afterlife. Its radical exploration of and experimentation with language have inspired generations of thinkers and poets since—most notably John Milton, whose Paradise Lost owes much of its conception of language and its strikingly visual imagery to Prudentius's poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristian poetry, LatinvTranslations into English. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aPOETRY / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aMalamud, Martha A.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146305140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463051423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801463051/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK